  • 81% of the SWEEPING observations are missing, I suggest we remove it from the analysis.

  • for other categories, Id simply remove rows with missing load weight.

plot_ts_by_type <- function(grouped_df, start_year=2000, end_year=2021, categories_list = clean_waste$Load.Type){
  grouped_df %>% 
  filter(lubridate::year(week) >= start_year,
         lubridate::year(week) <= end_year,
         Load.Type %in% categories_list) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = week, y = med_weight)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45)) +
  facet_wrap(Load.Type ~ .) +
  labs(title = 'Median waste weight per week',
       subtitle = 'broken down by load type',
       x = NULL,
       y = NULL)
}

plot_ts_by_type(grouped_waste)

Here are some issues that need to be addressed with the data:

  1. Load.Type categories dont seem mutually exclusive.

This could be because over time, recycling streams got split into different categories or some categories changed in the way the data is collected. We can manually pick the load types we want to include in the analysis. In this case, I recommend keeping: Brush, Bulk, Dead animal, Garbage collections, Litter, Mixed Litter, Recycled Metal, Recycling - single stream, Tires and Yard Trimming.

  1. The time series is incomplete for some load types. We need to decide on a cut off date. I recommend 2005

  2. There are some extreme values in the load weight that need to be removed from the analysis. I recommend using an outlier detection technique de decide on what observations are likely to be data errors, or outliers not containing information about the time series.

We will apply the outlier detection below. Here is the plot of the data, taking into account the recommendations above.

load_type_list <- c('RECYCLING - SINGLE STREAM', 'BULK', 'YARD TRIMMING', 'BRUSH', 'GARBAGE COLLECTIONS', 'TIRES', 'LITTER', 'MIXED LITTER', 'DEAD ANIMAL', 'RECYCLED METAL')
  
plot_ts_by_type(grouped_waste, start_year = 2005, end_year = 2021, categories_list = load_type_list)

One last issue is that some route types are not matching the load type they are collecting.

It seems to be quite frequent, although not very common. Could it be that indeed a route thats supposed to collect metal collected some yard trimmings? Or is it a manual data error? This could be dealt with by an outlier detection algorithm that would get rid of observations that are likely to be data errors.

Outliers removal

There is one load weight value that is negative in a recycling collection.

There are a few values that are close to 0 or exactly 0 - they might not be a problem

clean_waste %>% 
  filter(Load.Weight <= 1)  %>%
  arrange(-Load.Weight)
detect_outliers <- function(load_type){
  
  df <- clean_waste %>%
    filter(Load.Type == load_type) %>% 
    select(Load.ID, Load.Weight)
  
  iforest <- isolationForest$new()
  
  iforest$fit(df)
  
  #predict outliers within dataset
  df$pred <- iforest$predict(df)
  
  threshold <- df$pred$anomaly_score %>% quantile(0.95)
  
  df$outlier <- as.factor(ifelse(df$pred$anomaly_score >= threshold, "outlier", "normal"))
  
  df %>%
    select(Load.ID, Load.Weight, outlier)
}
outliers_predictions <- map_dfr(load_type_list, detect_outliers)
grouped_waste_no_outlier <- clean_waste %>%
  left_join(outliers_predictions, by = c('Load.ID', 'Load.Weight')) %>%
  filter(outlier != 'outlier') %>%
  mutate(week = lubridate::floor_date(lubridate::as_date(Load.Time), unit = 'week')) %>%
  group_by(week, Load.Type) %>%
  summarise(av_weight = mean(Load.Weight, na.rm = T),
            med_weight = median(Load.Weight, na.rm = T),
            load_nb = n_distinct(Load.ID),
            trucks_nb = n_distinct(Route.Number)) %>%
  ungroup()
